1
00:01:40,395 --> 00:01:42,438
This is Russo. Please leave a message.

2
00:01:42,439 --> 00:01:43,982
He's not answering my calls.

3
00:01:43,983 --> 00:01:46,233
It's over, and he must know it.

4
00:01:46,234 --> 00:01:49,236
You don't think there's
any way he can recover?

5
00:01:49,237 --> 00:01:52,949
The Republicans will play that interview
on every radio and television station

6
00:01:52,950 --> 00:01:55,451
from now until November 5th.

7
00:01:55,452 --> 00:01:58,913
I sympathize with the kid, but this
was my concern from the beginning.

8
00:01:58,914 --> 00:02:01,206
And I should've listened to you, sir.

9
00:02:01,207 --> 00:02:03,960
I thought he could handle the pressure.

10
00:02:03,961 --> 00:02:06,004
Okay. So he withdraws.

11
00:02:06,005 --> 00:02:07,588
We need to replace him.

12
00:02:07,589 --> 00:02:09,757
You have any ideas?

13
00:02:09,758 --> 00:02:13,136
With less than two months to go?

14
00:02:13,137 --> 00:02:15,972
If the President hadn't shut
me out of the early discussions,

15
00:02:15,973 --> 00:02:18,099
I could've come up with some good options,

16
00:02:18,100 --> 00:02:20,977
but I don't know anyone who's got
the name recognition and donor base

17
00:02:20,978 --> 00:02:25,523
to start a campaign from
scratch just seven weeks out.

18
00:02:25,524 --> 00:02:27,733
Let me think.

19
00:02:29,152 --> 00:02:32,113
Everything hinges on
the next few minutes...

20
00:02:32,114 --> 00:02:36,408
all my months of planning,
every move I've made.

21
00:02:38,786 --> 00:02:42,040
- There is one person.
- Who?

22
00:02:43,833 --> 00:02:45,877
You, Mr. Vice President.

23
00:02:47,754 --> 00:02:50,464
If you ran to reclaim your seat,

24
00:02:50,465 --> 00:02:52,008
I think you'd win by a landslide.

25
00:02:52,009 --> 00:02:53,676
Resign the vice presidency.

26
00:02:53,677 --> 00:02:55,761
Only if you win.

27
00:02:55,762 --> 00:02:57,930
Walker needs me for 2016.

28
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:02,518
Are you entirely certain he's
gonna keep you on the ticket?

29
00:03:02,519 --> 00:03:05,188
I mean, it's no secret

30
00:03:05,189 --> 00:03:08,607
the two of you don't exactly get along.

31
00:03:08,608 --> 00:03:10,401
What has he said?

32
00:03:12,403 --> 00:03:15,948
Oh, you're putting me in a very
awkward position, Mr. Vice President.

33
00:03:15,949 --> 00:03:18,534
Has he been bad-mouthing me?

34
00:03:18,535 --> 00:03:23,122
Well, the exact phrase he
used was "pain in the ass."

35
00:03:28,502 --> 00:03:29,879
That fucker.

36
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:32,006
He's got no idea how to lead,

37
00:03:32,007 --> 00:03:34,550
no sense of respect.

38
00:03:34,551 --> 00:03:36,719
- Oh, is this his idea?
- No.

39
00:03:36,720 --> 00:03:39,013
- His way of getting rid of me?
- No. It struck me yesterday,

40
00:03:39,014 --> 00:03:40,765
and I just thought it was worth suggesting.

41
00:03:40,766 --> 00:03:42,558
But, no, I haven't
discussed this with anyone.

42
00:03:42,559 --> 00:03:44,393
And you shouldn't.

43
00:03:44,394 --> 00:03:48,022
People don't leave the White
House to become a governor.

44
00:03:50,150 --> 00:03:52,902
May I ask you a personal question, sir?

45
00:03:52,903 --> 00:03:55,487
Do you want to be the Vice President?

46
00:03:55,488 --> 00:03:59,242
Peter said that when you were
out on that campaign trail,

47
00:03:59,243 --> 00:04:02,078
you had so much enthusiasm and energy

48
00:04:02,079 --> 00:04:06,415
that he thought you maybe
missed being the Governor.

49
00:04:08,542 --> 00:04:10,377
I do miss it.

50
00:04:10,378 --> 00:04:12,713
Then why not go back?

51
00:04:12,714 --> 00:04:14,924
You could be the hero of this election

52
00:04:14,925 --> 00:04:19,053
and secure Pennsylvania
for the Democrats in 2016.

53
00:04:19,054 --> 00:04:23,057
Garrett would never go along
with something like this,

54
00:04:23,058 --> 00:04:25,059
even if he hates my guts.

55
00:04:25,060 --> 00:04:26,936
It would make him look weak,

56
00:04:26,937 --> 00:04:30,064
like he's lost control
of the administration.

57
00:04:30,065 --> 00:04:32,316
Not if it was a mutual decision.

58
00:04:33,276 --> 00:04:35,486
Look, let me talk to Garrett.

59
00:04:35,487 --> 00:04:37,905
I won't mention that we've spoken.

60
00:04:39,991 --> 00:04:43,035
I suppose there's no harm in
finding out what he thinks.

61
00:04:43,036 --> 00:04:45,621
Thank you, Mr. Vice President.

62
00:04:48,874 --> 00:04:53,587
- Slogans for 400.
- "1976. He's making us proud again."

63
00:04:53,588 --> 00:04:55,506
- D.J.
- Who is Carter.

64
00:04:55,507 --> 00:04:57,842
- No. John.
- Who is Ford.

65
00:04:57,843 --> 00:05:00,678
- Peter?
- Slogans for 600.

66
00:05:00,679 --> 00:05:05,099
- "1888. Grandfather's hat fits Ben."
- Peter, are you here?

67
00:05:05,100 --> 00:05:07,143
- Claudia.
- Who is Benjamin Harrison.

68
00:05:07,144 --> 00:05:10,104
- Yes.
- Presidential slogans for 800.

69
00:05:10,105 --> 00:05:12,940
- "1900... "
- On the train ride down,

70
00:05:12,941 --> 00:05:14,900
I almost called the police
to have them break in

71
00:05:14,901 --> 00:05:17,611
and make sure you hadn't hurt yourself.

72
00:05:17,612 --> 00:05:21,406
I'm not gonna even ask you what
happened. It doesn't matter right now.

73
00:05:21,407 --> 00:05:24,618
- "1964. In your heart, you know he's right."
- What matters right now...

74
00:05:24,619 --> 00:05:26,954
- what matters...
- Who is Goldwater.

75
00:05:28,455 --> 00:05:30,124
- Claudia
- Who is Goldwater.

76
00:05:30,125 --> 00:05:31,709
Barry Goldwater. Yes.

77
00:05:35,297 --> 00:05:37,965
Oh, come on. Hey, I'm watching that.

78
00:05:41,511 --> 00:05:44,471
What matters is the 50 reporters
in front of your building

79
00:05:44,472 --> 00:05:47,975
and the 150 campaign staffers who
don't know if they still have a job.

80
00:05:47,976 --> 00:05:50,144
It's over.

81
00:05:51,436 --> 00:05:54,023
I know.

82
00:05:54,024 --> 00:05:56,525
So, tell them to go away.

83
00:06:09,747 --> 00:06:13,000
What, are you just gonna hole yourself
up in here and hope it all goes away?

84
00:06:13,001 --> 00:06:14,668
Yeah, that's pretty much the plan.

85
00:06:14,669 --> 00:06:17,171
Well, I won't let you.

86
00:06:17,172 --> 00:06:20,716
Hey, put that down. Hey.

87
00:06:20,717 --> 00:06:23,386
- Hey, put that down!
- Peter...

88
00:06:38,859 --> 00:06:41,653
We need to put out a statement.

89
00:06:41,654 --> 00:06:43,906
Call me when you're prepared to do that.

90
00:06:46,158 --> 00:06:49,078
I'll be at the headquarters in Philly.

91
00:06:53,166 --> 00:06:55,709
I was scared that I was starting to feel

92
00:06:55,710 --> 00:06:59,588
too much for you.

93
00:06:59,589 --> 00:07:02,507
I think that's why I ended it.

94
00:07:02,508 --> 00:07:04,427
And you have no room for fear?

95
00:07:04,428 --> 00:07:07,388
No. Being afraid doesn't
accomplish anything.

96
00:07:07,389 --> 00:07:09,723
That's not true. When I'm overseas,

97
00:07:09,724 --> 00:07:12,435
rational fear... disease or violence...

98
00:07:12,436 --> 00:07:15,229
that sort of fear keeps you alive.

99
00:07:15,230 --> 00:07:18,107
Back here, God,

100
00:07:18,108 --> 00:07:19,984
I find myself afraid of things

101
00:07:19,985 --> 00:07:23,570
that I can't name or point to.

102
00:07:23,571 --> 00:07:27,366
It's like, uh, how little am I seeing?

103
00:07:27,367 --> 00:07:30,995
Or have I wasted this day or this moment?

104
00:07:30,996 --> 00:07:33,080
Yeah, I think that sometimes...

105
00:07:33,081 --> 00:07:35,874
whether my life will add up.

106
00:07:37,376 --> 00:07:40,129
Francis would roll his eyes

107
00:07:40,130 --> 00:07:42,798
if he heard me talking like this.

108
00:07:45,343 --> 00:07:47,470
Does he know where you are?

109
00:07:48,846 --> 00:07:50,931
No, he doesn't.

110
00:08:00,565 --> 00:08:03,694
If he's looking for you,
that's where you are.

111
00:08:03,695 --> 00:08:06,405
Over there.

112
00:08:06,406 --> 00:08:08,449
Before you met Frank.

113
00:08:08,450 --> 00:08:10,493
Alone.

114
00:08:10,494 --> 00:08:12,453
Curious.

115
00:08:12,454 --> 00:08:14,913
Absorbing everything.

116
00:08:14,914 --> 00:08:18,292
You have no idea what I
was like when I was a girl.

117
00:08:20,419 --> 00:08:22,671
Did he ever know that side of you?

118
00:08:24,756 --> 00:08:28,177
He wasn't interested in that girl.

119
00:08:28,178 --> 00:08:30,095
And neither was I.

120
00:08:30,096 --> 00:08:32,139
What were you interested in?

121
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:34,350
Being more than an observer.

122
00:08:34,351 --> 00:08:36,394
You wanted to be seen.

123
00:08:36,395 --> 00:08:38,854
Not just seen.

124
00:08:38,855 --> 00:08:41,857
I wanted to be significant.

125
00:08:49,115 --> 00:08:51,158
There's no historical precedent.

126
00:08:51,159 --> 00:08:53,494
Aaron Burr ran for Governor,
Calhoun for the Senate.

127
00:08:53,495 --> 00:08:57,373
200 years ago. One shot a man in a
duel, the other believed in slavery.

128
00:08:57,374 --> 00:08:59,624
Is that really the sort of
company we wanna share, Frank?

129
00:08:59,625 --> 00:09:03,128
Mr. President, we stand losing
control of an important swing state,

130
00:09:03,129 --> 00:09:06,382
our majority in the house, and quite
possibly your second term in office.

131
00:09:06,383 --> 00:09:09,718
Preventing all of that may
require unconventional measures.

132
00:09:09,719 --> 00:09:11,512
It would look like I'm pushing him out.

133
00:09:11,513 --> 00:09:14,598
Or worse... that he's
abandoning the administration.

134
00:09:15,849 --> 00:09:17,809
You make a joint statement.

135
00:09:17,810 --> 00:09:20,145
You say he won't resign unless he wins.

136
00:09:20,146 --> 00:09:23,690
If he loses, he stays on as Vice President.

137
00:09:23,691 --> 00:09:26,860
No one could accuse either of
you of disloyalty to the other.

138
00:09:26,861 --> 00:09:29,613
- Did Jim come to you with this?
- No. It's entirely my idea.

139
00:09:29,614 --> 00:09:32,824
I wouldn't dream of speaking to the Vice
President without passing it by you first.

140
00:09:32,825 --> 00:09:34,701
I think he'd take it as an affront,

141
00:09:34,702 --> 00:09:37,037
like I'm trying to get rid of him.

142
00:09:37,038 --> 00:09:40,374
Honestly, sir, I think he might be
more interested than you imagine.

143
00:09:40,375 --> 00:09:43,168
- Why is that?
- Well, I hesitate to bring this up,

144
00:09:43,169 --> 00:09:46,589
but when he was campaigning for Russo,

145
00:09:46,590 --> 00:09:50,426
he spoke quite freely about you, sir.

146
00:09:52,928 --> 00:09:56,056
Mm-hmm. Tell me.

147
00:09:56,057 --> 00:09:58,392
Of course, I'm getting
this secondhand from Peter,

148
00:09:58,393 --> 00:10:00,311
but the gist of it is that...

149
00:10:00,312 --> 00:10:02,896
that you lack entirely in leadership,

150
00:10:02,897 --> 00:10:05,983
and that you have no sense of respect.

151
00:10:05,984 --> 00:10:08,026
And he wants more responsibility.

152
00:10:08,027 --> 00:10:10,028
And how do I give him that when he shows

153
00:10:10,029 --> 00:10:12,948
absolutely no discretion, no discipline?

154
00:10:12,949 --> 00:10:14,908
Well, that is entirely my point. Now, look,

155
00:10:14,909 --> 00:10:16,910
I take full responsibility
for backing Russo,

156
00:10:16,911 --> 00:10:19,580
but there could be a
silver lining in all this.

157
00:10:19,581 --> 00:10:21,457
You could accomplish two goals:

158
00:10:21,458 --> 00:10:23,708
Secure Pennsylvania for the Democrats

159
00:10:23,709 --> 00:10:27,421
and find an honorable
way to replace Matthews.

160
00:10:27,422 --> 00:10:29,089
What do you think?

161
00:10:30,215 --> 00:10:32,259
I think it is a very big decision,

162
00:10:32,260 --> 00:10:34,219
and we do not want to make it impulsively.

163
00:10:34,220 --> 00:10:36,721
I agree. I'd like to put
some more thought into it.

164
00:10:36,722 --> 00:10:38,890
Well, that is very prudent,
sir. Just bear in mind,

165
00:10:38,891 --> 00:10:41,059
seven weeks out, that every day counts.

166
00:10:54,239 --> 00:10:56,659
- Hi, sir.
- How much is it?

167
00:10:56,660 --> 00:10:59,244
Oh, I got your receipt right here.

168
00:11:04,375 --> 00:11:07,419
No, no, no. It was... it was just $40.

169
00:11:07,420 --> 00:11:10,589
Yeah. Don't tell anyone, all right?

170
00:11:12,007 --> 00:11:14,468
No. I... I never say
anything about our tenants.

171
00:11:16,053 --> 00:11:17,971
- The press still outside?
- Yeah.

172
00:11:17,972 --> 00:11:20,015
I told them you weren't
here, like you said.

173
00:11:20,016 --> 00:11:22,725
Most of them left. There's
still, you know, a few, though.

174
00:11:22,726 --> 00:11:25,812
If I wanted to leave, is there a
place I could do it without being seen?

175
00:11:25,813 --> 00:11:28,148
Yeah. The freight elevator
down to the garage.

176
00:11:28,149 --> 00:11:32,069
- I could call you a cab or...
- All right. Thanks. I'll let you know.

177
00:11:32,070 --> 00:11:34,071
Mr. Russo, uh...

178
00:11:34,072 --> 00:11:35,947
sir, it's none of my business,

179
00:11:35,948 --> 00:11:39,618
but, uh, my Uncle... he fell
off the wagon a few times.

180
00:11:39,619 --> 00:11:42,329
When he did, the best thing for
him was just not to be alone.

181
00:11:42,330 --> 00:11:44,915
I'll give you this money back,
I'll take that bag off your hands,

182
00:11:44,916 --> 00:11:46,709
come in here, keep you company...

183
00:11:46,710 --> 00:11:49,420
I appreciate it. I'll let
you know if I change my mind.

184
00:13:41,657 --> 00:13:43,742
Sit down.

185
00:13:45,994 --> 00:13:47,912
Where's Claire?

186
00:13:47,913 --> 00:13:50,123
Not here.

187
00:13:50,124 --> 00:13:53,418
So what is this, tying up loose ends?

188
00:13:53,419 --> 00:13:56,505
I wouldn't presume.

189
00:13:56,506 --> 00:13:59,550
People like you can't be neatly tied up.

190
00:13:59,551 --> 00:14:01,552
But I thought perhaps we could start...

191
00:14:32,332 --> 00:14:34,793
It's very tasteful.

192
00:15:12,623 --> 00:15:16,042
This is the dress she wore to the gala.

193
00:15:16,043 --> 00:15:17,878
I believe so.

194
00:15:17,879 --> 00:15:19,755
It is.

195
00:15:19,756 --> 00:15:21,799
I recognize it.

196
00:15:27,930 --> 00:15:30,014
Go back into the bedroom.

197
00:15:50,243 --> 00:15:53,956
I'm amazed how well you got her in focus.

198
00:16:01,171 --> 00:16:03,214
What should we call her?

199
00:16:04,132 --> 00:16:06,176
Why does she need a name?

200
00:16:06,177 --> 00:16:09,137
I never photograph anyone
without knowing their name.

201
00:16:09,138 --> 00:16:12,015
You didn't take the photograph. I did.

202
00:16:13,475 --> 00:16:16,812
I think we should call her Claire.

203
00:16:18,146 --> 00:16:21,525
She doesn't even look like me.

204
00:16:21,526 --> 00:16:23,902
Not even a younger version.
Why do you keep saying that?

205
00:16:23,903 --> 00:16:26,697
Not her features, her expression.

206
00:16:26,698 --> 00:16:29,700
Hey, we should mount it. You
can hang her in your house.

207
00:16:29,701 --> 00:16:31,994
Would Francis object?

208
00:16:34,454 --> 00:16:37,582
Can we please not discuss Francis?

209
00:16:37,583 --> 00:16:39,417
You brought him up in the park.

210
00:16:39,418 --> 00:16:41,545
I know I did, and I shouldn't have.

211
00:16:41,546 --> 00:16:44,381
So we have to pretend he doesn't exist?

212
00:16:52,806 --> 00:16:56,434
I thought we could talk about anything.

213
00:16:56,435 --> 00:16:59,980
He is a presence here. You must admit that.

214
00:16:59,981 --> 00:17:02,440
When you walked through the door yesterday,

215
00:17:02,441 --> 00:17:05,027
he walked right in with you.

216
00:17:06,028 --> 00:17:08,446
It's just me, nobody else.

217
00:17:08,447 --> 00:17:12,242
You keep telling yourself
that, it might come true.

218
00:17:16,997 --> 00:17:20,542
How do you think she'd feel
if she knew I was wearing this?

219
00:17:20,543 --> 00:17:22,920
I don't know.

220
00:17:24,379 --> 00:17:27,298
You don't think she'd be upset?

221
00:17:27,299 --> 00:17:31,094
She'd probably say you
look very beautiful in it.

222
00:17:32,679 --> 00:17:35,139
It's like steel.

223
00:17:37,141 --> 00:17:39,185
You should put it back.

224
00:17:43,147 --> 00:17:45,067
I think I'll keep it.

225
00:17:45,068 --> 00:17:48,528
I'll buy you one of
your own, if you'd like.

226
00:17:48,529 --> 00:17:51,155
No. I want this one.

227
00:17:51,156 --> 00:17:53,867
She came into my bedroom.

228
00:17:53,868 --> 00:17:56,453
She should know I came into hers.

229
00:18:01,374 --> 00:18:04,168
Is your bed always so perfectly made?

230
00:18:04,169 --> 00:18:06,630
It's a habit I formed at military school.

231
00:18:06,631 --> 00:18:11,051
What side of the bed does she sleep on?

232
00:18:12,385 --> 00:18:14,471
That side.

233
00:18:33,406 --> 00:18:35,700
She can keep it.

234
00:18:36,660 --> 00:18:38,703
Fits her better anyway.

235
00:19:23,498 --> 00:19:25,583
Listen, Zoe...

236
00:19:26,543 --> 00:19:29,129
Whatever just happened upstairs,

237
00:19:29,130 --> 00:19:31,131
whatever these past six months have been,

238
00:19:31,132 --> 00:19:34,885
can we agree that it is time to simplify?

239
00:19:34,886 --> 00:19:36,845
What does simple look like?

240
00:19:36,846 --> 00:19:40,724
We maintain our professional arrangement,

241
00:19:40,725 --> 00:19:44,102
as you suggested, which I will honor.

242
00:19:44,103 --> 00:19:46,188
You still trust me?

243
00:19:48,356 --> 00:19:50,608
What choice do I have?

244
00:19:50,609 --> 00:19:53,361
You didn't hurt me

245
00:19:53,362 --> 00:19:56,031
or discard me like you said you would.

246
00:20:00,994 --> 00:20:03,914
I'm glad I didn't have to.

247
00:20:05,456 --> 00:20:09,544
Yes, we'll agree to simplify.

248
00:20:10,461 --> 00:20:12,255
Good.

249
00:20:32,984 --> 00:20:36,404
Sorry I'm a few minutes late, Frank.

250
00:20:40,617 --> 00:20:43,578
Please, have a seat.

251
00:20:46,998 --> 00:20:49,500
I have a pretty good idea why
you asked for this meeting.

252
00:20:49,501 --> 00:20:53,004
- Have you and the President had a chance to speak?
- We have.

253
00:20:53,005 --> 00:20:56,091
- Is he leaning one way or another?
- He's torn.

254
00:20:57,801 --> 00:21:00,178
- And what about you?
